snippet.textDisplay: You know what else is popular? Linking to Stranger Things unnecessarily. It's the most lazy tired form of critique. Kids in peril and discovering  awesome things is not something Stranger Things invented. These are things kids relate and fantasize about. If anything, it has a Spielbergian and Dante-ish going for it which was what Stranger Things was going for anyway. This movie is directly connecting to the 80s when Ghostbusters came out. That familiar feeling is that connection to the past not because it is aping Stranger Things. It is more about the subject matter which is connected strongly to another time rather than it trying to be another show. This, however, has a modern feel in terms of cinematography and characters while still staying in touch with its past. It's pretty organic, really.

snippet.textDisplay:
Please.. jay.. rich.. it’s all fine, really. But let’s not forget what the original ghostbusters were: scientists. Each had 1 or 2 science degrees. They knew what they were doing. And sometimes, even they weren’t entirely sure of it. Which was both funny AND added priceless comedy to it. Here.. you have kids. Pre-pubescent and teenagers. And you want them to handle “unauthorized nuclear accelerators” that can “melt your face off” if mishandled...? Ok... fine. It’s extremely irresponsible and isn’t funny at all but... we’ll go along. And about the Shandor relationship.. we wanna imply Egon was related to him? well shandor was sort of a ghostbuster himself... as he was able to draw them and channel them into a building... and the shandor ghost was the main thing in the ghostbusters video game from a few years ago, with some of the original cast involved AND plot was straight out from Dan Aykroyd and was what he imagined ghostbusters 3 was supposed to be, had they ever done it...
But you want kids pick up the legacy? Have them go to college and become scientists first cause “a proton pack is not a toy”.

snippet.textDisplay:
If you want Ghostbusters 3, play Ghostbusters: The Video Game from 2009. A great way to tie up a trilogy, and it even ended with a perfect setup for a game or movie sequel that I'm annoyed neither this new film or Ghostbusters 2016 took up: a Ghostbusters business expansion (not exactly a franchise, but close) in LA, led by someone trained by the original team.
You could do whatever you want with a new team on the other side of the country in a vastly different city. It could've been like a spin-off/reboot in one!

The Cartoon series made me a believe that Ghostbusters has a lot more potential for future content than just a one hit wonder. It's a formula that works and can be reused. My favorite episode of the cartoon version btw was when they were stuck on a farm. And the undead would surface at night but then have to go back into the ground when the dead rooster crows.

They were all pinned in the farm shed with like 1,000 corpses ripping away at the place and in snap they just stop, turn around and moan as they march back into the ground non chalante. And you had that creepy bag pipe music.

Two, the fact that its a new incarnation and seems like an original script based one the trailer, lets hope they do not trope too much off of 1984. Third I do like the IMDB listed cast, which includes:

Paul Rudd
Billy Murray
Annie Potts
Sigourney Weaver
Finn Wolfhard
Dan Aykroyd
Ernie Hudson

Sadly one which is missing is Rick Moranis.

I hope they can balance the cast and film.

snippet.textDisplay: Too much humor draws GB2016 and Marvel Studios comparisons so I think they got it right. I think Ghostbusters was always (to some extent)  about world building. The idea of it being a business with franchise potential, unique stuff likeTobins Spirit Guide, and the scientific and occult aspects easily leaves a lot of room for imagination and creativity. Hollywood just rarely gets sequels right, because it's more about capturing lightning, and selling that same lightning as much as they can. As far as the Egon stuff, he was a literal dude so I think he literally collected mold and spores, and it wasn't him just being funny, that's why it was funny.
